title: S&P 500 ends higher after strong bank earnings
summary:
STORY: U.S. stocks ended mostly higher on Wednesday, with the exception of the Dow, which closed roughly flat. The S&P 500 gained four-tenths of a percent while the tech-heavy Nasdaq added two-thirds of a percent.

U.S. Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent helped ease investors' nerves by saying that Washington did not want to escalate a trade conflict with China. He also emphasized that President Trump is ready to meet Chinese President Xi Jinping later this month.

Meanwhile, a day after Fed Chair Jerome Powell left the door open to rate cuts, Fed Governor and Trump appointee Stephen Miran said at a CNBC event that "two more cuts this year sounds realistic."

Both are part of an economic backdrop that should help propel the bull rally even higher, says Sean O'Hara, president of PacerETFs Distributors.

"I think the market overall is in a pretty good place. You know, I like it. For example, when we have something like yesterday happened where the futures were negative and then all throughout the day, the market seemed to climb. And so that to me is an indication that there are still buyers out there. I think the overall environment sets up pretty good. We're coming into earnings season. I think we're going to get decent earnings from people, probably better earnings growth than what's been forecast. You know, Jerome Powell is acting like maybe he's going to cut again, which would be good news for the market as well."

Among Wednesday's stock moves, Morgan Stanley jumped more than 4.5% to a record high, while Bank of America also rose roughly 4.5% after the heavyweight lenders beat Wall Street estimates for third-quarter profit on dealmaking strength.

Shares of data center firms rose, including Applied Digital, which surged more than 7.5%. The moves followed news that an investment consortium including BlackRock, Microsoft and Nvidia will buy Aligned Data Centers, one of the world's biggest data center operators, in a $40 billion deal. 

And shares of Bunge jumped almost 13% despite the grain trader lowering its 2025 earnings forecast following its merger with Viterra.
